text: Nature and origin of the violet stains on the walls of a Roman tomb Irene Dominguez-Moñino a,1, Marta Diaz-Herraiz a,1, Valme Jurado a, Leonila Laiz a, Ana Z. Miller a, Juan Luis Santos b, Esteban Alonso b, Cesareo Saiz-Jimenez a,⁎ a Instituto de Recursos Naturales y Agrobiologia, IRNAS-CSIC, Avenida Reina Mercedes 10, 41012 Sevilla, Spain b Escuela Politecnica Superior, Universidad de Sevilla, Virgen de Africa 7, 41011 Sevilla, Spain • The walls and ceiling of the Circular are Mausoleum tomb, biodeteriorated by microorganisms. • Violet stains are produced by a strain of Streptomyces parvus isolated from the walls. • The violet pigment is composed of granaticins, compounds soluble in alka- line media. • The pigment diffuses to the mortar and surrounding substrata during wetting periods. Saiz-Jimenez). j o u r n a l h o m e p a g e : w w w . e l s e v i e r . c o m / l o c a t e / s c i t o t e n v Science of the Total Environment G R A P H I C A L A B S T R A C T

The Circular Mausoleum tomb (Roman Necropolis of Carmona, Spain) dates back from the ﬁrst century AD and is characterized by a dense microbial (phototrophic) colonization on the walls and ceiling. However, some walls ex- hibited an important number of violet stains of unknown origin. The microbial communities of these violet stains are mainly composed of cyanobacteria, streptomycetes and fungi. A strain of Streptomyces parvus, isolated from the walls, produces a violet pigment in culture media. High performance liquid chromatography-mass spectrom- etry of the culture extracts obtained from this Streptomyces revealed the presence of a few granaticins, pigments with a benzoisochromanequinone structure. When metabolically active in the tomb, S. parvus synthesizes the pigments that diffuse into the mortar. During rain and/or wetting periods, the pigments are solubilized by alka- line waters and elute from the starting position to the surrounding mortar, enlarging the pigmented area and thus contributing to this exceptional biodeterioration phenomenon. Science of the Total Environment 598 (2017) 889–899 Contents lists available at ScienceDirect derived from environmental factors and the opening of the tombs to public visits. One of the most complex phenomena observed in these sites is biodeterioration. Subsurface environments (caves, necropolises, catacombs, tombs, crypts, etc.) are characterized by their microclimatic conditions, mainly high relative humidity the year round, lower temperatures than outside and poor ventilation (Saiz-Jimenez et al., 2011; Diaz-Herraiz et al., 2014; Fernandez-Cortes et al., 2015; Cañaveras et al., 2015). These conditions © 2017 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.

promote the growth of Actinobacteria, a common phylum in tombs, with Nocardia, Pseudonocardia and Streptomyces as the most abundant genera (Diaz-Herraiz et al., 2013, 2014). Actinobacteria produce colored bioﬁlms on mural paintings (Agarossi, 1994; Ettenauer et al., 2014) and many species of this phylum are characterized by the production of pig- ments (Waksman and Lechevalier, 1953; Bérdy, 2005). The Circular Mausoleum is a small tomb located in the Roman Ne- cropolis of Carmona, Spain. This tomb is actively colonized by photosyn- thetic microorganisms as reported by Cañaveras et al. (2015). However, these authors did no investigate the nature and origin of the abundant violet stains that can be observed on the walls (Fig. 1). The colored stains have been noticeable since the last quarter of the 20th century and increased over time. The presence of violet stains on mural paint- ings and walls is rare. They were only reported in two Etruscan tombs whose pigments were not identiﬁed (Agarossi, 1994). A few sampling campaigns were conducted in the Circular Mausole- um to analyze the microbial communities associated with the stains and to know the chemical structure of the violet pigment. To this aim Bacte- ria, Archaea and Eukaryota were investigated. In different samplings pe- riods we isolated three strains of Streptomyces involved in the production of a diffusible violet pigment in laboratory cultures. The iso- lation of strains that produce violet pigments, either in nature or in the laboratory, together with the identiﬁcation of the metabolites permitted to disclose the nature of this biodeterioration phenomenon. 2.1. Sampling of violet stains and cultivation assays

In December 2012, a sampling campaign was conducted in the Cir- cular Mausoleum tomb from the Roman Necropolis of Carmona, Spain. A few violet stains were collected from the walls (Fig. 1) using a steril- ized scalpel, and placed into sterile tubes and used for different analyses. Three types of samples were selected: GB1 from green bioﬁlm (near to violet stains), GV2 from an area where green bioﬁlms and violet stains were in close contact, and VS3 from violet stains far from green bioﬁlms. GV2 and VS3 samples were used for molecular analyses and VS3 for Fig. 1. Violet stains in the Circular Mausoleum, Roman Necropolis of Carmona, Spain. A. Entrance to the tomb. B. End of the tomb. C. Details of violet stains from A and neighbour phototrophic bioﬁlms. D. Detail of violet stains from B. (For interpretation of the references to color in this ﬁgure legend, the reader is referred to the web version of this article.) I. Dominguez-Moñino et al. / Science of the Total Environment 598 (2017) 889–899 bacterial isolation. VS3 sample was processed the day of sampling, suspended in a saline solution and inoculated on Petri plates with a TSA (tryptone soy agar) medium with 0.2% glycerol. Cultures were incu- bated at 30 °C for several weeks to allow the development of slow grow- ing species. Samples for nucleic acid analyses were preserved in the laboratory at −80 °C until being processed. Only one strain producing violet pigments (MCs36) was obtained from the 2012 sampling. Previously, a few more sampling campaigns were carried out seeking for the isolation of this type of bacteria. Only in the 1997 (strain MC48) and 2005 (strain MC05) campaigns we were able to isolate two more strains producing the pigment.

A few Streptomyces from culture collections were used in this study: Streptomyces parvus DSM 40348T, Streptomyces pluricolorescens DSM 40019T, Streptomyces cyaneofuscatus DSM 41423T, Streptomyces vietnamensis DSM 41927T, Streptomyces badius DSM 40139T, Streptomy- ces sindenensis DSM 40255T, Streptomyces globisporus DSM 40199T and Streptomyces rubiginosohelvolus DSM 40176T. Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2) was kindly provided by Dr. Paloma Liras, Molecular Biology De- partment, University of Leon, Spain. 2.2. Field emission scanning electron microscopy Small mortar fragments from the Circular Mausoleum tomb exhibiting green bioﬁlms and violet stains were examined by ﬁeld emission scanning electron microscopy (samples GB1, GV2 and VS3). Fresh samples were ﬁxed with 2.5% glutaraldehyde in 0.1 M cacodylate-buffer (pH 7.4) at 4 °C for 2 h and washed thrice in cacodylate-buffer. Subsequently, they were postﬁxed in 1% osmium tetroxide for 1 h at 4 °C and dehydrated by subsequent dilution se- ries in ethanol and acetone ﬁnishing with 100% acetone before dry- ing. The samples were dried in a critical point drying device (Leica EM 300) at 34.5 °C. Finally, the mortar samples were mounted on SEM stubs and sputter-coated with gold. FESEM examinations were performed in a FEI TENEO microscope, which was operated in secondary electron detection mode with an acceleration potential of 5 kV. 2.3. Characterization of microbial communities by molecular analysis

Total nucleic acids from violet stain samples were extracted using the method described by Grifﬁths et al. (2000) for the parallel analysis of DNA and RNA, which allowed the identiﬁcation of total community and metabolically active microorganisms, respectively. Extracted nucleic acids were re-suspended in 80 μl of sterile ultrapure water. For RNA analysis, a 50 μl aliquot was subjected to a DNase digestion step using an RNase-Free DNase (Qiagen GmbH, Hilden, Germany), and RNA was puriﬁed using the RNeasy MinElute Cleanup kit (Qiagen GmbH, Hilden, Germany), according to the manufacturer's instructions. Complementary DNA (cDNA) from the puriﬁed RNA was synthesized using Superscript II Reverse Transcriptase (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA, USA) with a speciﬁc reverse primer: 907R for bacteria (Muyzer et al., 1995), Cya781R for cyanobacteria (Nübel et al., 1997), StrepF for Strep- tomyces (Rintala et al., 2001), and ITS4 for fungi (White et al., 1990), at a temperature of 42 °C for 50 min.

The PCR reaction mixture (50 μl) consisted of 5 μl of 10× PCR buffer, 2 μl of MgCl2 (50 mM), 0.5 μl of each primer (50 μM), 5 μl of dNTP (2 mM each), 5–10 ng of DNA template and 0.25 μl of Taq polymerase (5 U μl− 1) (Bioline, GC Biotech, the Netherlands), made up to 50 μl of nuclease-free water (Sigma-Aldrich, USA). PCR ampliﬁcations were per- formed in BioRad iCycler thermal cycler (BioRad, CA, USA). PCR condi- tions for bacteria and cyanobacteria consisted of: 2 min of initial denaturing step at 94 °C, followed by 35 cycles of denaturing at 94 °C for 15 s, annealing at 55 °C for 15 s and a 1 min extension at 72 °C, with a ﬁnal extension of 10 min at 72 °C. The PCR ampliﬁcation protocol for Streptomyces consisted of denaturing step of 5 min at 98 °C, followed by 30 cycles of denaturing at 95 °C for 1 min, 52 °C for 40 s, and 72 °C for 2 min and a ﬁnal 10 min elongation at 72 °C. PCR conditions for the am- pliﬁcation of ITS regions were as following: 2 min at 94 °C, followed by 35 cycles at 94 °C for 1 min, at 50 °C for 1 min, and at 72 °C for 1 min, with ﬁnal extension at 72 °C for 5 min. Reactions were performed in triplicate, and negative controls without DNA template were run for all PCR reactions. All PCR products were inspected on 1% (w/v) agarose gels and puri- ﬁed using the JetQuick PCR Puriﬁcation Spin Kit (Genomed, Löhne, Germany). 2.4. Construction of DNA-RNA clone libraries

The puriﬁed products were ligated into plasmid vector pCR®4- TOPO® and subsequently transformed into chemically competent Escherichia coli cells from the TOPO TA Cloning Kit (Invitrogen, Carlsbad, CA), according to manufacturer's instructions. Clones were sequenced by MACROGEN Europe Sequencing Services (Amsterdam, The Netherlands). Sequence data were edited using the software BioEdit and checked for chimera by Bellerophon using a variety of window sizes (200–400 bp) and corrections. Putative chimeric sequences were excluded from further analysis. The selected sequences were aligned using the program MUSCLE (Edgar, 2004) and the respective distance matrices were generated by PHYLIP program. The resulting matrices were used as input for DOTUR (Schloss and Handelsman, 2005) in order to assign sequences to operational taxonomic units (OTUs) using the furthest neighbour algorithm at different evolutionary dis- tances (0–10%) and to generate the respective rarefaction curves. For each OTU, one clone was chosen as a representative sequence. Taxo- nomic classiﬁcation was done using the BLASTN algorithm (Altschul et al., 1990) for homology search in the NCBI and EzTaxon databases. 2.5. Identiﬁcation of isolates by 16S rRNA and multilocus sequence analysis Genomic DNA of the strains MCs36, MC48 and MC05 were extracted from cultures grown for 3 days on tryptone soy agar at 30 °C according to Marmur (1961). The 16S rRNA genes were ampliﬁed following the method described by Laiz et al. (2009). In addition, the following ﬁve I. Dominguez-Moñino et al. / Science of the Total Environment 598 (2017) 889–899

housekeeping genes were studied for multilocus sequence analysis (MLSA): atpD (ATP synthase β-subunit), gyrB (DNA gyrase β-subunit), recA (recombinase A), rpoB (RNA polymerase β-subunit) and trpB (tryp- tophan synthase β-subunit). The primers for ampliﬁcation and se- quencing of atpD, recA, rpoB and trpB, and the PCR conditions were described previously by Guo et al. (2008). The primers for gyrB were redesigned by Rong et al. (2009). PCR products were sequenced by SECUGEN Sequencing Services (Madrid, Spain). The accession numbers of the sequences of 16S rRNA, atpD, gyrB, recA, rpoB and trpB genes de- posited in GenBank were displayed in Table 2 and Supplementary Table 3.

The sequences of the 16S rRNA and the other ﬁve housekeeping genes of the studied strains were trimmed manually (Guo et al., 2008) and were concatenated head-to-tail in frame to generate a sequence in the order 16S rRNA-atpD-gyrB-recA-rpoB-trpB (Maciejewska et al., 2015). The 16S rRNA gene sequences were identiﬁed using the global alignment algorithm on the EzTaxon-e (Kim et al., 2012) and the se- quences of the closest related Streptomyces species were retrieved. For the MLSA the closest related strains and their sequences were obtained through the BLAST algorithm (Altschul et al., 1990) in the GenBank da- tabase by the National Centre for Biotechnology Information and the Streptomyces MLST database (http://pubmlst.org/streptomyces). Se- quences of each gene and the closest related strains were multiply aligned using MUSCLE (Edgar, 2004). Phylogenetic trees based on the concatenated sequences and on the six genes were constructed using the neighbour-joining (Saitou and Nei, 1987), maximum-likelihood (Felsenstein, 1981) and maximum-parsimony methods in MEGA6 (Tamura et al., 2013). The trees robustness was evaluated using a boot- strap analysis of 1000 resamplings. 2.6. DNA-DNA hybridization DNA-DNA hybridization of the strain MCs36 with respect to the strains MC05, MC48, S. parvus DSM 40348T, S. sindenensis DSM 40255T, S. pluricolorescens DSM 40019T, S. badius DSM 40139T, S. globisporus DSM 40199T and S. rubiginosohelvolus DSM 40176T was performed ac- cording to Urdiain et al. (2008). A liquid medium containing yeast extract, peptone, malt extract, glu- cose, sucrose and MgCl2 was used for pigment production as described by Hopwood et al. (1985). The pigments were extracted with ethyl acetate.

HPLC analyses were performed as described by Martín et al. (2015). Brieﬂy, 20 μl of extract sample were diluted to 100 μl using methanol and 20 μl of diluted extract were injected. Liquid chromatographic anal- yses were performed on an Agilent 1200 series HPLC (Agilent, USA) consisting of a vacuum degasser, a binary pump, an autosampler and a thermostated column compartment. Separation of studied compounds was achieved using a Zorbax Eclipse XDB–C18 Rapid Resolution HT (4.6 × 50 mm i.d.; 1.8 μm) analytical column (Agilent, USA). Elution was carried out with acetonitrile (containing formic acid 0.1%, v/v) (sol- vent A) and aqueous 10 mM ammonium formate solution (containing formic acid 0.1%, v/v) (solvent B), at a ﬂow rate of 0.6 ml/min with the column thermostated at 25 °C. The elution program used was: 0– 7.5 min: linear gradient from 10% to 35% of solvent A, 7.5–14.5 min: isocratic 35% solvent A, 14.5–14.6 min: linear gradient from 35% to 100% of solvent A, 14.6–18.5 min: isocratic 100% solvent A. Mass spec- trometry analyses were performed on a 6410 QqQ instrument equipped with an electrospray ionization source (Agilent, USA). Ionization of analytes was carried out using the following settings: MS capillary volt- age: 3000 V, drying-gas ﬂow rate: 9 l/min, drying-gas temperature: 350 °C and nebulizer pressure: 40 psi. Each extract was measured using scan and product ion modes. First- ly, scan mode was applied to the determination of the retention time of

each of the studied compounds. Scan was carried out using positive po- larity and applying a voltage to the exit end of the capillary (fragmentor) of 50 V. Mass spectra were registered from m/z 80 to 950. Product ion mode was carried out, using positive polarity, for the monitorization of the ions of m/z 445, 447, and 559, corresponding to ions [M+1]+ of granaticin A, dihydrogranaticin A, and granaticin B, re- spectively. The applied fragmentor was 50 V and the voltage applied to the ions in the collision cell (collision energy) was 12 V. MS/MS spectra from m/z 50 to 570 were obtained using a scan time of 300 ms. Mass spectra of the granaticins were reported elsewhere (Diaz-Herraiz et al., 2016). 3.1. Field emission scanning electron microscopy (FESEM) Abundant green bioﬁlms were observed coating the interior walls of the Circular Mausoleum tomb, while violet stains were also found in dif- ferent positions, such as in close contact with the green bioﬁlms, and also near and far from them (Fig. 1C, D). FESEM examinations of sample GB1 revealed a network of entangled cyanobacterial ﬁlaments showing

true branching (Fig. 2A, branching in the left center of the ﬁgure). This type of branching is characteristic of Iphinoe spelaeobios and it is a fun- damental diagnostic character in the taxonomy of stigonematalean cyanobacteria (Lamprinou et al., 2011). The cylindrical ﬁlaments have a diameter of about 2.5–3 μm (Fig. 2B), and their sheaths are usually cal- ciﬁed as observed in Fig. 2C. These morphological features are consistent with the cyanobacterium I. spelaeobios, corroborating the DNA data ob- tained in this work (Table 1 and Supplementary Table 1). In sample GV2, bacterial ﬁlaments and cells of different sizes (b1 μm in diameter) are associated with the cyanobacterial ﬁlaments (Fig. 2D); these bacte- rial ﬁlaments likely correspond to actinobacteria. Fig. 2E–G from sample VS3 shows tangled aerial hyphae and arthrospores, characteristic of Streptomyces. 3.2. Identiﬁcation of microbial communities The microbial communities associated with the violet stains were identiﬁed using DNA and RNA-based molecular analyses. DNA analysis provided data on the total microorganisms present in the violet stains, while RNA discriminated the metabolically active members of the com- munity at the sampling time. Both analyses revealed the presence of a Table 1 A. Phylogenetic afﬁliation of the 16S rRNA gene sequences of total bacteria from violet stains. Circular Mausoleum, Roman Necropolis of Carmona. B. Phylogenetic afﬁliation of the 16S rRNA gene sequences of metabolically active bacteria from violet stains. Circular Mausoleum, Roman Necropolis of Carmona.

variety of microorganisms belonging to different phyla. Clone libraries were performed using speciﬁc primers for bacteria (Table 1, sample GV2), cyanobacteria (Supplementary Table 1, sample GV2), streptomy- cetes (Table 2, sample VS3) and fungi (Supplementary Table 2, sample GV2). A total of 513 high-quality sequences were obtained. Among total bacteria (DNA-based analysis) the majority of clones were afﬁliated to Cyanobacteria (62.7%), Alphaproteobacteria (16.9%), Actinobacteria (9.6%), Betaproteobacteria (4.8%), Gammaproteobacteria (3.6%), and Firmicutes (2.4%). The complex microbial community from the violet stains contained, fungi. in addition to bacteria and cyanobacteria, Among bacteria, six different species of the genus Streptomyces were identiﬁed from the DNA-based clones (total Streptomyces population), and the most abundant (57.6%) was a member of the taxonomic group Streptomyces hygroscopicus (Table 2A). In this group it was difﬁcult to identify the species due to the fact that four species showed similar 16S sequences: S. demainii, S. endus, S. hygroscopicus subsp. hygroscopicus and S. sporocinereus. The RNA-based clones (metabolically active bacteria) yielded seven dif- ferent species of the genus Streptomyces, among them the most abundant (45.5%) was S. qinglanensis (Table 2B). However, the member of the taxonomic group S. hygroscopicus only represented 9.1% of active Streptomyces. Rarefaction curves derived from the clone libraries (Supplementary Fig. 1) indicated that the full extent of diversity was reached in the case of metabolically active bacteria and cyanobacteria and for total and met- abolically active fungi. For the total population of bacteria the curve was near the asymptote indicating that the number of sequences cloned was sufﬁcient to identify most of the species. No rarefaction curve is presented for Streptomyces as we used a speciﬁc primer for this single genus. Table 3 shows that 17 Streptomyces from a total of 28 bacteria were isolated from the violet stains in the 2012 campaign (sample VS3). From all Streptomyces only one strain (MCs36) produced a diffusible violet pigment under laboratory conditions. In previous campaigns we isolat- ed two more strains producing violet pigments, strains MC48 in 1997 and strain MC05 in 2005 (Supplementary Fig. 2). On the basis of the 16S rRNA gene sequences similarity, the three studied strains are most closely related to several species belonging to the taxonomic group Streptomyces griseus. In addition, we relied on DNA–DNA hybridization (DDH) that is a major tool in microbial spe- cies delineation and represents the most important criterion for valid species description (Staley, 2006; Goris et al., 2007). DDH values ≤ 70% are considered as an indication that the tested organism belongs to a different species than the type strain used as reference (Tindall et al., 2010). Supplementary Table 4 showed DDH values well above 90% for the strains MCs36, MC48, and MC05 indicating that these strains are mem- bers of the same species (Wayne et al., 1987). In addition, DDH value be- tween strain MCs36 and S. parvus DSM 40348T was 71.9%, which classiﬁes strain MCs36 as a S. parvus. DDH values between the strain MCs36 and the type strains S. sindenensis DSM 40255T, S. badius DSM 40139T, S. globisporus DSM 40199T, S. rubiginosohelvolus DSM 40176T and S. pluricolorescens DSM 40019T were below 70%, indicating that them were not related at species level. Streptomyces parvus MCs36, a recent isolate from the tomb, pro- duced a violet pigment in culture media. Dominguez-Moñino et al. / Science of the Total Environment 598 (2017) 889–899 Biological colonization caused by photosynthetic microorganisms was widespread on the walls and ceiling of the Circular Mausoleum, which was noticeable as green patches and/or extensive bioﬁlms, as re- ported by Cañaveras et al. (2015) (Fig. 1). However, the violet stains were only located in the upper part of the walls, an appropriate niche for cyanobacteria because they were especially successful on the ceiling and adjacent walls due to a better adaptation to dryness. In fact, the ceil- ing reaches high temperatures in summer due to insolation.

In nature, microbial communities undergo cycles (wetting-dryness, nutrients shortage, bioactive substances production, etc.). Natural growth conditions results in discontinuous and limited colony develop- ment, as suggest the different sizes of violet spots (Fig. 1), which point to the formation of unstable assemblages along the time, and depletion of nutrients or summer dryness which induces dormancy and sporulation. Of importance was the ﬁnding in the Circular Mausoleum of cyanobacteria associated with the violet stains. Two recently described cyanobacteria, I. spelaeobios, isolated from a Greek cave, and Loriellopsis cavernicola, isolated from a Spanish cave, were identiﬁed in this tomb using molecular methods (Lamprinou et al., 2011). These cyanobacteria were also identiﬁed by microscopy in the tomb of Servilia, at some 100 m from the Circular Mausoleum, a drier and ventilated environ- ment, but without violet stains. Therefore molecular data agree with previous microscopic studies from this and other tombs at this necrop- olis. In fact, both cyanobacteria are components of natural populations in subterranean environments where dim light is a major stress factor. The cyanobacterium I. spelaeobios constituted nearly all the active cyanobacterial community in the violet stains, but on the contrary, the presence of other cyanobacteria was almost negligible, although they were also active (Table 1). Streptomyces parvus strain MCs36 was part of a complex microbial community dominated by the cyanobacterium I. spelaeobios to which apparently were associated a few different species of the genus Strepto- myces. An association between cyanobacteria and streptomycetes was found in St. Callixtus and Domitilla catacombs (Albertano and Urzì, 1999; Urzì et al., 2017). Several adaptive advantages of cyanobacteria associated with Streptomyces have been reported, such as the preservation of the cyanobacterial viability and functional activity on drying and a stimulating effect on the nitrogen-ﬁxing ability (Zvyagintsev et al., 2010).

Streptomyces were not represented among the clones sequenced in Table 1 and were only evidenced using speciﬁc primers (Table 2). The absence of Streptomyces in Table 1 is not surprising. It is well-known that universal primers cannot efﬁciently amplify all targets, which casts doubts on the universality of such primers. However, Streptomyces strains dominated the isolates due to the presence of spores in the samples and their growth in the culture media used (Table 3). Pigment production by S. parvus strain MCs36 was sufﬁcient to orig- inate the violet stains when this strain was active in the tomb, likely when nutrients were available in raining periods through soil percola- tion. Streptomyces parvus strain MCs36 and nearest relatives from the S. griseus taxonomic group (Fig. 2) were searched in the literature for pigment production. Shirling and Gottlieb (1968, 1972) reported that S. rubiginosohelvolus produced either a yellow or no pigment at all in several media; no pigment other than traces of yellow was found on cul- ture media for S. parvus; and no pigment was produced by S. sindenensis and S. pluricolorescens. However, Ayukawa et al. (1969) reported that a strain of S. pluricolorescens showed a purple to brown soluble pigment in culture media. S. badius had no distinctive pigment and S globisporus produced a light yellow to greenish yellow pigment (Shirling and Gottlieb, 1972). Shirling and Gottlieb (1972) stated that the reverse side of the colo- ny of the type species of S. parvus showed no distinctive pigments (light yellow to light greenish yellow) on yeast-malt agar, oatmeal agar, salts- starch agar, and glycerol-asparagine agar. These pigments were not pH sensitive when tested with 0.05 N NaOH or HCl, so denoting the absence of quinone functional groups.

Dominguez-Moñino et al. / Science of the Total Environment 598 (2017) 889–899 A literature search reported the production of some metabolites by strains of S. parvus such as polypeptides and lipopeptides of white to yellow color (Rao et al., 2013). The data revealed that S. parvus strains did not produce violet pigments and this was also conﬁrmed in our lab- oratory with cultures of the type strains of S. parvus (Supplementary Fig. 3), and other members of the S. griseus taxonomic group, such as S. rubiginosohelvolus, S. cyaneofuscatus and S. pluricolorescens, in TSA me- dium or using a speciﬁc medium for pigment production (Hopwood et al., 1985). Therefore, the strain MCs36 of S. parvus, isolated from the Circular Mausoleum, is a new producer of violet granaticins. This strain is to be added to the Streptomyces species producing violet: S. coelicolor (Hopwood, 1999), S. violaceus (Waksman and Lechevalier, 1953), S. violaceoruber (Brimble et al., 1999), S. vietnamensis (Zhu et al., 2007), or dark blue pigments: S. caeruleatus (Zhu et al., 2011), S. shaanxiensis (Lin et al., 2012), etc.

It is well-known that different Streptomyces species can produce the same pigments and their presence or absence among strains of a single species was variable (Waksman and Lechevalier, 1953). This could ex- plain why the type species of S. parvus cannot produce violet pigments, as opposite to our S. parvus strain MCs36 (Fig. 4). For pigment identiﬁcation we used S. coelicolor A3(2) and S. vietnamensis as representative species for violet pigment production and for comparison with the strains MCs36 of S. parvus. High performance liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (HPLC-MS) revealed that the violet pigment produced by the strain MCs36 was mainly composed of granaticin derivatives (Fig. 3). In fact, HPLC-MS conﬁrmed the presence of three main pigments, dihydrogranaticin A, granaticin A and granaticin B, in the culture ex- tracts from S. parvus, strain MCs36 (Fig. 3) and S. vietnamensis type strain. The production of dihydrogranaticin A by S. vietnamensis was not previously detected by Deng et al. (2011). Granaticins show antibac- terial activity against Gram-positive bacteria (Brimble et al., 1999). The presence of granaticins A and B in the violet stains and its anti- bacterial activity against Gram-positive bacteria justify the low number of clones of Gram-positive bacteria displayed in Table 1 (Rubrobacter radiotolerans and Ornithinibacillus contaminans), and enhanced the presence of clones from Gram-negative bacteria and cyanobacteria. However, a few more Gram-positive bacteria were isolated from the vi- olet stains, as shown in Table 3. Most of these bacteria were representa- tive of sporulating species whose spores can be transported by air and deposited (and/or entrapped) on the photosynthetic bioﬁlm, and likely this justiﬁes their growth and isolation in culture media.

To conclude, the origin of the violet stains in the Circular Mausoleum is the presence of a strain of S. parvus, a member of a complex microbial community thriving on the tomb walls. In growing periods, the Strepto- myces excretes the soluble violet granaticins, compounds with a benzoisochromanequinone structure (Snipes et al., 1979), which diffuse into the mortar. One of the major violet pigments, granaticin A, was detected in the tomb walls by using analytical pyrolysis (Diaz-Herraiz et al., 2016). Granaticin A is soluble in alkaline water but the solubility of the pigment decreased with pH value. The pH of carbonated lime mortars is near 9, which permitted the solubilization of the pigment and the diffusion into the substratum during wetting periods. In favourable periods, the pigment is solubilized by alkaline waters and elutes from the starting position to the surrounding mortar, enlarging the pigmented area as denoted by an in- creasing intensity on the stain edges and a lower intensity or absence in the stain center (Fig. 1D). This is also supported by a photographic moni- toring of the violet stains from the Circular Mausoleum, extending from 1997 to 2005 (Rogerio Candelera et al., 2008). The utilization of image analysis based on Principal Component Analysis veriﬁed a growth pattern along this period where some stains increased its colored area up to 69%. The S. parvus strain was active for long time in the tomb, as it was isolated in different years along two decades of study, and disseminated randomly on the mortar. Dispersion of spores was also favoured by van- dalic etching that transports their spores along the mortar incisions, promoting the appearance of new violet stains.

In cultural heritage research we rarely have the opportunity to iso- late a microorganism and reproduce in the laboratory the synthesis of pigments which cause the deterioration phenomenon, as shown here. Similar violet stains were also observed on the mural paintings from the Tomb of the Chase and Fishing and the Tomb of the Bulls, Tarquinia, Italy (Supplementary Fig. 4). These Etruscan tombs were sampled in July 2009. Nineteen Streptomyces species were isolated from the Tomb of the Chase and Fishing and six from the Tomb of the Bulls but none produced violet pigments. This could be explained by the absence of Streptomyces producing violet pigments because a cleaning and restora- tion process was carried out about two years before sampling. Most like- ly the original Streptomyces assemblages were removed in the restoration process and the isolated strains were re-colonizers. The dominance of Streptomyces, either in Roman tombs as reported here, in catacombs (Albertano and Urzì, 1999; Krakova et al., 2015) or Etruscan tombs (Agarossi, 1994) highlights the ability of species of this genus to colonize subsurface environments, a fact also observed in many caves (Groth et al., 1999; Maciejewska et al., 2016).
